Aug 10 2006	Exceptionally good value and very nice for the price	I have just returned from London where I spent a total of nine days at the Thanet Hotel in London's Bloomsbury -a very convenient area for shopping and going to the theater and right near the British Museum and interesting restaurants. The Thanet at 8 Bedford Place has a bright blue awning and boxes of lush blooming flowers on either side of the steps to the entrance. The rooms are bright and cheerful with colorful bedspreads and drapes. The single rooms are rather small for a stay of more than 2 or 3 days, but the owners will allow you to stay in a larger room at the single price if there is one available. (In the recent heatwave,small had the advantage as the fan provided quickly cooled the room.) There is a dining room on the ground floor overlooking the street where a very good English breakfast is served, with lots of choices, including great sausages brought in from the country. Richard and Lynwen Orchard, the owners and managers, are very friendly and thoughtful concerning their guests needs. It has become a home away from home for me.	
Jul 29 2006 	Fawlty Towers!	We booked a quad room at this hotel through Laterooms(--) based on the positive reviews on this website and the pictures and descriptions on the hotel's own website. We were looking forward to a cozy and welcoming B&amp;B. We should have paid more attention to the review entitled &quot;Avoid the 3rd floor at all costs&quot;. When we arrived at the hotel, they insisted that we sign in before showing us our room (we should have seen the red flag right there), but we were tired after a 15 hour train trip and checked in first. We were shown to room 15 on the 3rd floor. Albert did help with the luggage, but the stairs to the 3rd floor were so steep as to make me worry about my children's and my own safety. Once in the room, things did not get any better. While it was clean and had a fireplace, there is nothing else positive I can say about it. The floor was tilted so badly that the head was lower than the foot of the beds, the bathroom was so tiny that you needed a shoehorn to get in and out of it, and the floor creaked so badly when you walked on it that anyone getting up in the middle of the night would certainly wake everyone else up. The worst thing, though, was the heat. Room 15 used to be the attic, and it is directly under the roof. We arrived during a heat wave (a rare event to be sure), but the room was sweltering. There was only 1 tiny window. Albert suggested that we keep the curtains closed and stay out during the day, returning to the room only at night when it might be cooler, which to me was not a solution. What is the point of having a hotel room if you can't go there except to sleep? We sometimes like to rest a bit before going out in the evening, for example. We asked about getting a fan, but there was none to be had. After 15 minutes in the room, we decided we couldn't take it anymore, and called our 2nd choice hotel, which had a room available.When we came downstairs with our luggage, we told them we were leaving, and when it became clear that there was no way we would stay without being given a different room, they offered to call us a cab. We accepted their offer, but they instead called a private car hire service (no doubt getting a little kickback in the process), which turned out to be more expensive than a city cab would have been. When I contacted the manager (who was out of town when this happened) to request that he waive the cancellation fee of one night's stay since we had not been offered a satisfactory room in the first place, he instead told us that because we had booked through Laterooms, he was obligated to charge us for all 3 days of our planned stay. It was only after I contacted Laterooms and my credit card company that he agreed to refund us 2 of the 3 nights. Needless to say, we won't be back.	
Jul 27 2006 	Not as it used to be	This was our third stay at the Thanet and it will likely be the last. I still adore the location and the room was fine: small but clean and comfortable with nice tea making service. However, we stayed for five days and it was probably the last day before the breakfast servers and one of the two men at the desk decided to smile. We travel often and prefer small hotels and B&amp;Bs; we almost always feel welcomed and enjoy chatting with the folks who work there. Not the case this time. The older woman who served us in the breakfast room made us feel like we were imposing simply by sitting at the table. The same offerings each morning also got a bit tiresome so perhaps we just stayed too long. The atmosphere simply was not friendly.Next time, we'll pay a bit more and stay elsewhere.	
Jun 22 2006	Stairs to 3rd Floor a killer	The location of this hotel is excellent. We had a triple room, which was roomy enough - but it was on the top floor and as there is no lift the only way up is the stairs! I knew before I booked that there was no lift, but I wasn't prepared for the stairs...the first level is not a problem, the 2nd level is a little more, but the 3rd level is like stairs up to an attic, very steep and narrow. If you are supremely fit with no luggage, you won't be bothered, but we had large suitcases (travelling from Australia for 5 weeks) and we are all fit, but my husband has a niggly knee from an accident and the stairs caused it to flare up, so we had to carefully plan our itinerary to avoid using the stairs more than necessary. Staff do not offer to help with your luggage (no wonder). If you can be assured of a room on the first floor, I wouldn't hesitate staying there again as the location couldn't be better and the cost in comparison to a lot of London accommodation is good. But avoid the 3rd floor at all costs.	
Apr 24 2006	nice hotel	Thanet Hotel in London is really a good choice if you don't need luxury. It is small but nice and clean; our room was spatious (we are a family of four people); towels were changed every day; breakfast was good and all the staff was friendly. Then, the place is very quiet; it is close to the British Museum and other central attractions; it is not far both from Russel Square and Holborn tube stations. We recommend it.	
Feb 4 2006	Nice little hotel	We spent 4 nights in the Thanet hotel in April 2005. The location is perfect to visit London, it is at a calm road. We had a room going to the garden side, which we can recommand. However, it is quite central, the Britisch museum is around the corner and it's a nice walk to Covent Garden and near to 2 underground stations. The service was very good, breakfirst nearly too opulent, the rooms were small but clean with an own bath room and you could make tea and coffee in the room (including fresh cookies every day!).	
Aug 31 2005	Great location delightful staff at the Thanet	Bloomsbury is a great central location to visit London. Plenty of buses, tube and walking distance of the theatres, British Museum etc. Also lots of eateries and little shops for bits and pieces, as well as a bigger grocery store near Holborn tube. Russell Sq and Bloomsbury Sq are nearby and very pleasant to sit in. I stayed 7 nights at the Thanet starting on 19 August 2005. it was great. Staff very helpful, especially Richard, Albert and George. The room was not big (London rooms are never big) but it had everything I needed including a recently renovated ensuite shower, washbasin and WC (also not big but perfectly adequate). The cooked breakfast (with cereal, yogurt, fruit for starters, if you can fit it in!) is excellent. Really sets you up for a days sightseeing. My room overlooked the garden and was very quiet. I can recommend this hotel and will stay there again.	
Aug 18 2005	Thanet Worked Great for Family of 5	The Thanet Hotel in London has a perfect room for a family of 4 or 5. Its location on Bedford Place is very close to the British Museum and other popular tourist attractions, and is close to family-priced restaurants and a grocery store near the Holborn tube station. We stayed downstairs in room 16, which had a double bed and 3 twin-size beds. It also had two ensuite bathrooms, one with a toilet and sink, the other with a shower and sink. The room was comfortable and very clean. Nice and quiet. No noticable street noise, even with the windows open. Nothing glitzy or fancy, but all the basic necessities were there. The full English breakfast included was very good. The staff is friendly and quite helpful. We will definitely recommend the Thanet to our friends, and will stay there again if we return to London.	
